  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the process to get a brand name trademarked in India?",
  "response": "Trademarking a brand name in India involves several steps. Here\u2019s a detailed process:\n\n1. **Preliminary Search**: Conduct a trademark search to ensure that your brand name is unique and not already registered by someone else. This can be done through the official website of the Controller General of Patents, Designs, and Trade Marks (CGPDTM), or you can hire a professional to do this for you.\n\n2. **Application Filing**: If your brand name is available, you can file a trademark application. This can be done online through the official website (IP India) or offline by submitting the required forms at the Trademark Registrar Office.\n\n3. **Documentation**: Prepare the necessary documents, which typically include:\n   - Form TM-A for trademark application.\n   - Details of the applicant (name, address, etc.).\n   - Brand name/logo.\n   - Description of goods/services to be trademarked.\n   - Power of Attorney (if the application is filed by a lawyer or agent).\n   - Priority claim (if applicable).\n\n4. **Payment of Fees**: Pay the required trademark application fee. The fee varies depending on the nature of the applicant (individual, startup, small enterprise, etc.) and can be checked on the IP India website.\n\n5. **Examination**: After filing, the application is scrutinized by the trademark examiner. They check for any discrepancies and ensure compliance with legal requirements. If there are any issues, they will raise objections.\n\n6. **Publication in Trademark Journal**: If the examiner finds the application satisfactory, it is published in the Trademark Journal. This opens a window for third parties to oppose the registration if they believe the trademark infringes on their existing rights.\n\n7. **Opposition Period**: There is a 4-month opposition period after the publication. If no opposition is filed, or if opposition is filed and ruled in favor of the applicant, the process moves forward.\n\n8. **Registration**: If there are no oppositions or if oppositions are resolved in favor of the applicant, the trademark is registered, and a Certificate of Registration is issued.\n\n9. **Renewal**: A registered trademark in India is valid for 10 years, and it can be renewed indefinitely by filing a renewal application and paying the requisite fees.\n\nIt's highly recommended to consult with a trademark attorney or professional to ensure that the process is handled correctly and to mitigate any potential legal issues.",
